<subSubSection id="C30FC29A8E2FFFCCFF8CFEAA70EEFC05" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BAA91118E2FFFCCFF8CFEAA73A3FEB9" blockId="19.[113,1089,299,505]" box="[113,641,353,372]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFF8CFEAA706BFEB9" bold="true" box="[113,329,353,372]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
Status in 
<bibRefCitation id="EF84ECE08E2FFFCCFF3AFEAA7067FEB9" author="ZIMSEN E." box="[199,325,353,372]" firstAuthor="ZIMSEN" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" refId="ref19364" refString="ZIMSEN E. 1964: The type material of I. C. Fabricius. Munksgaard, Copenhagen, 656 pp." type="book" year="1964">ZIMSEN (1964)</bibRefCitation>
.
</emphasis>
P. 90; No. 1323 (no material listed).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA91118E2FFFCCFF8CFEB07008FE64" blockId="19.[113,1089,299,505]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFF8CFEB0700DFE43" bold="true" box="[113,303,379,398]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">Original description.</emphasis>
‘C. flavescens ferruginea thorace postice sinuato, coleoptris punctis undecim nigris. Habitat in Asia Mus. Britann.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA91118E2FFFCCFF6DFE7A7077FE34" blockId="19.[113,1089,299,505]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
Media. Antennae, caput, thorax aut flava, aut ferruginea, immaculata. Thoracis margo posticus sinuatus. Elytra punctis quinque, primo baseos, secundo, ad suturam, tertio in medio, quatro &amp; quinto pari, &amp; communi versus apicem.’ (
<bibRefCitation id="EF84ECE08E2FFFCCFF38FE2D7069FE34" author="FABRICIUS J. C." bookContentInfo="xx + 330 pp." box="[197,331,486,505]" firstAuthor="FABRICIUS" journalOrPublisher="Christ. Gottl. Proft, Hafniae" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" refId="ref18957" refString="FABRICIUS J. C. 1792: Entomologia systematica emendata et aucta. Secundum classes, ordines, genera, species adjectis synonymis, locis, observationibus, descriptionibus. Tom. I. [Pars I]. Christ. Gottl. Proft, Hafniae, xx + 330 pp." title="Entomologia systematica emendata et aucta. Secundum classes, ordines, genera, species adjectis synonymis, locis, observationibus, descriptionibus. Tom. I. [Pars I]" type="book" year="1792">FABRICIUS 1792</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA91118E2FFFCCFF8CFDDA703AFD85" blockId="19.[113,1089,529,968]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFF8CFDDA7001FDE5" bold="true" box="[113,291,529,552]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">Current status.</emphasis>
Junior synonym and primary junior homonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C15EA928E2FFFCCFCA7FDDA7036FD85" authority="(Olivier, 1790)" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1790" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Basiprionota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFCA7FDDA7562FDE5" box="[858,1088,529,552]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">Basiprionota sinuata</emphasis>
(Olivier, 1790)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA91118E2FFFCCFF8CFD9A733BFCC5" blockId="19.[113,1089,529,968]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFF8CFD9A71C2FDA5" bold="true" box="[113,224,593,616]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">Remarks.</emphasis>
So far, we have been unable to ¿nd any specimen in the collection which might represent potential 
<typeStatus id="54AE2FB38E2FFFCCFEC0FDBA7049FD45" box="[317,363,625,648]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C15EA928E2FFFCCFE73FDBA70DEFD45" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[398,508,625,648]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Basiprionota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFE73FDBA70DEFD45" box="[398,508,625,648]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">C. sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Judging from the description we are not sure whether the species was correctly synonymized with 
<taxonomicName id="4C15EA928E2FFFCCFDB4FD5A7278FD65" authority="(Olivier, 1790)" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[585,858,657,680]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Basiprionota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFDB4FD5A7397FD65" box="[585,693,657,680]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">B. sinuata</emphasis>
(Olivier, 1790)
</taxonomicName>
because the latter has differently positioned spots on elytra and with one spot on marginalia which was not mentioned by Fabricius. 
<taxonomicName id="4C15EA928E2FFFCCFEC3FD1A733DFD25" baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[318,543,721,744]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Basiprionota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinuata">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFEC3FD1A733DFD25" box="[318,543,721,744]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">Basiprionota sinuata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a very variable species but it never has a spot on the suture, as in Fabricius’s description.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA91118E2FFFCCFF6DFCDA70EEFC05" blockId="19.[113,1089,529,968]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">
<bibRefCitation id="EF84ECE08E2FFFCCFF6DFCDA700AFCE5" author="ZIMSEN E." bookContentInfo="656 pp." box="[144,296,785,808]" firstAuthor="ZIMSEN" journalOrPublisher="Munksgaard, Copenhagen" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" refId="ref19364" refString="ZIMSEN E. 1964: The type material of I. C. Fabricius. Munksgaard, Copenhagen, 656 pp." title="The type material of I. C. Fabricius" type="book" year="1964">ZIMSEN (1964)</bibRefCitation>
did not report any material for this species. However, it is possible that the species belongs to a quite different genus and any surviving 
<typeStatus id="54AE2FB38E2FFFCCFCFDFCFA720CFC85" box="[768,814,817,840]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">type</typeStatus>
specimen(s) are standing unnoticed under a different species name. We processed in detail most of the BMNH Cassidinae, with the exception of the old world Cassidini and 
<taxonomicName id="4C15EA928E2FFFCCFD2DFCBA725FFC45" authorityName="Chapuis" authorityYear="1875" box="[720,893,881,904]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="684" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Aspidimorphini">Aspidimorphini</taxonomicName>
. There is a chance that the 
<typeStatus id="54AE2FB38E2FFFCCFF34FC5A71D5FC65" box="[201,247,913,936]" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">type</typeStatus>
could still be hidden among this material, but it is certainly not present in the main collection of 
<taxonomicName id="4C15EA928E2FFFCCFEC7FC7A70E7FC05" authorityName="Chevrolat" authorityYear="1836" box="[314,453,945,968]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Basiprionota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="676" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9614D038E2FFFCCFEC7FC7A70E7FC05" box="[314,453,945,968]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="676">Basiprionota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
